# {{.Name}} — Claude Guidelines

## Build & Test

```bash
make dev            # Run dev server (auto-generates templ + live reload)
make build          # Build binary (generates templ first)
make test           # Run tests
make lint           # Run linters
make docker-up      # Start PostgreSQL
make docker-down    # Stop PostgreSQL
```

## Framework

This project uses the HAMR framework (`github.com/FyrmForge/hamr`). Key packages:

- `hamr/pkg/server` — Echo wrapper with functional options
- `hamr/pkg/respond` — Content-negotiated responses (HTML/JSON)
- `hamr/pkg/validate` — Validation helpers (return "" or error string)
- `hamr/pkg/middleware` — Auth, CSRF, flash, rate limiting, etc.
- `hamr/pkg/db` — Database connection with retry + migrations
- `hamr/pkg/config` — Environment variable helpers
- `hamr/pkg/logging` — Structured logging (slog)
- `hamr/pkg/htmx` — HTMX request/response helpers

## Key Patterns

- Handlers: constructor injection, one package per domain
- Config: `config.GetEnvOrDefault()` helpers read environment variables
- Routes: registered in `internal/web/server.go`
- Responses: `respond.Negotiate(c, status, jsonData, templComponent)`
- Validation: `validate.Required(v)` returns "" or error message
- Flash: `middleware.SetFlash(c, msg, type)` before redirect
- Errors: custom handler in `internal/web/handler/errors/`

## Code Style

- Follow existing patterns in the codebase
- Use `hamr/pkg` helpers instead of reimplementing
- Prefer `respond.HTML`/`respond.Negotiate` over raw `c.HTML()`
- Add `// GET /path` comments above handler methods
- Keep handlers thin — business logic in service layer
